body: So we don't yet support Python 3.6 but we think it _should_ work and thanks for trying it out. Can you tell us in more detail about the problem(s) you're seeing?

I imagine that @chai2010 tried to install from an environment that is incapable of *building* gRPC Python (as most Windows environments are). We require a *nix-like environment to build on Windows (e.g. MSYS2), as we have C99 code and the ancient compilers provided for Python-building by Microsoft do not support C99 (or C++11 features, for `grpcio-tools`). Our explicitly supported Python versions are on PyPI via wheels, while I expect py3.6 installs to require a build-from-source-package.

Though, more information would be useful for understanding what the issue is.

Yeah, that's a build failure. That said, you also appear to have a broken environment on top of that; I doubt you'd be hitting permission errors in a good environment.

You're basically stuck with: downgrading to Python 3.5, or building from source with [MSYS2](https://msys2.github.io/) (which will be hard), using Linux/Mac+Xcode, or waiting until we get Python 3.6 wheels building (which we can maybe do soon; we'll see).
@kpayson64: I think that this was fixed in the `1.1.3` release; do you agree?
